<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" ><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.1.1">Jekyll</generator><link href="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><link href="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><updated>2021-04-27T23:36:28-05:00</updated><id>https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/feed.xml</id><title type="html">Tyler’s SandBox</title><subtitle>Blog</subtitle><entry><title type="html">Understanding and Implementing Proximal Policy Optimization (Schulman et al., 2017)</title><link href="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/papers/2021/04/27/PPO.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Understanding and Implementing Proximal Policy Optimization (Schulman et al., 2017)" /><published>2021-04-27T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2021-04-27T00:00:00-05:00</updated><id>https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/papers/2021/04/27/PPO</id><author><name></name></author><category term="papers" /><summary type="html">Research in policy gradient methods has been prevalent in recent years, with algorithms such as TRPO, GAE, and A2C/A3C showing state-of-the-art performance over traditional methods such as Q-learning. One of the core algorithms in this policy gradient/actor-critic field is Proximal Policy Optimization Algorithm implemented by OpenAI.</summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/images/ppo.jpeg" /><media:content medium="image" url="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/images/ppo.jpeg" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry><entry><title type="html">RLpapers: List of Reinforcement Learning papers and codes</title><link href="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/papers/2021/04/17/RLPapers.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="RLpapers: List of Reinforcement Learning papers and codes" /><published>2021-04-17T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2021-04-17T00:00:00-05:00</updated><id>https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/papers/2021/04/17/RLPapers</id><author><name></name></author><category term="papers" /><summary type="html">RLpapers</summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/images/RLpapers.jpeg" /><media:content medium="image" url="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/images/RLpapers.jpeg" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry><entry><title type="html">Orbitron: Reinventing the wheels and its control algorithm</title><link href="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/project-showcase/2021/04/02/Orbitron.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Orbitron: Reinventing the wheels and its control algorithm" /><published>2021-04-02T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2021-04-02T00:00:00-05:00</updated><id>https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/project-showcase/2021/04/02/Orbitron</id><author><name></name></author><category term="project-showcase" /><summary type="html">Being a heavy Sci-fi fan myself, I always wondered: how would those spherical wheels from Tron and I-Robot work in real life? And this simple thought began the 6-month journey of Project Orbitron.</summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/images/1_orbitron/preview.png" /><media:content medium="image" url="https://tylertaewook.github.io/blog/images/1_orbitron/preview.png" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry></feed>